# Type Safety Conventions

## EquipmentItem / AmuletItem narrowing

`GameState` uses narrow types for equipment and amulet slots:

```typescript
equipmentSlot1: EquipmentItem | null;  // GameCardData & { type: 'weapon' | 'shield' | 'monster' }
amuletSlots: AmuletItem[];             // GameCardData & { type: 'amulet' }
equipmentSlot1Reserve: EquipmentItem[];
```

When assigning `GameCardData` to these fields in reducer patches, use explicit type assertions:

```typescript
// ✅ Assert when the runtime type is known to be correct
patch.equipmentSlot1 = { ...card, durability: maxDurability } as EquipmentItem;
patch.amuletSlots = state.amuletSlots.filter(a => a.id !== cardId) as AmuletItem[];
patch.equipmentSlot1Reserve = survivors as EquipmentItem[];

// ❌ Don't assign raw GameCardData — TypeScript will error
patch.equipmentSlot1 = card; // Error: GameCardData not assignable to EquipmentItem
```

Import from `game-board/types`:

```typescript
import type { EquipmentItem, AmuletItem } from '@/components/game-board/types';
```

## GameEventMap naming conventions

| Prefix | Use for | Example |
|--------|---------|---------|
| `combat:` | Combat flows, damage, block | `combat:monsterDamaged` |
| `equipment:` | Equipment equip/break/repair | `equipment:destroyed` |
| `card:` | Card draw/play/discard/flip | `card:discardShock` |
| `hero:` | Hero skill/magic UI | `hero:skillRequiresTarget` |
| `shop:` | Shop flows | `shop:discoverStarted` |
| `event:` | Dungeon event flows | `event:completed` |
| `waterfall:` | Waterfall phases | `waterfall:completed` |
| `ui:` | Generic UI (banners, prompts) | `ui:requestDice` |
| `interactive:` | Continuation responses | `interactive:diceResolved` |

Before creating a new event, check if it already exists — reuse existing events rather than creating duplicates.

## Seeded RNG — no Math.random()

All game-logic randomness must use `state.rng` from `game-core/rng.ts`:

```typescript
import { nextInt, nextBool, shuffle, pickRandom } from '../rng';

const { value: roll, rng: rng1 } = nextInt(state.rng, 1, 20);
const { items: shuffled, rng: rng2 } = shuffle(rng1, candidates);
// Always carry the updated rng into the returned state
patch.rng = rng2;
```

`Math.random()` is only acceptable for UI-only purposes (animations, particle effects) — never for game logic.
